## Why Real-time?

In today's data-driven world, stakeholders want to see metrics update live — not after a page refresh. Firebase's Firestore provides real-time listeners that push updates to clients instantly.

## Setting Up Firebase

First, initialize Firebase in your React project:

```tsx
import { initializeApp } from 'firebase/app';
import { getFirestore } from 'firebase/firestore';

const app = initializeApp(firebaseConfig);
export const db = getFirestore(app);
```

## Custom Hook for Real-time Data

I created a reusable hook that subscribes to Firestore collections:

```tsx
function useRealtimeCollection(collectionName: string) {
  const [data, setData] = useState([]);

  useEffect(() => {
    const q = query(collection(db, collectionName));
    const unsubscribe = onSnapshot(q, (snapshot) => {
      setData(snapshot.docs.map(doc => ({
        id: doc.id,
        ...doc.data()
      })));
    });
    return () => unsubscribe();
  }, [collectionName]);

  return data;
}
```

## Visualizing with Recharts

Recharts makes it easy to create responsive, animated charts:

```tsx
<ResponsiveContainer width="100%" height={300}>
  <LineChart data={realtimeData}>
    <Line type="monotone" dataKey="value" stroke="#8884d8" />
    <XAxis dataKey="timestamp" />
    <YAxis />
    <Tooltip />
  </LineChart>
</ResponsiveContainer>
```

## Handling Connection States

One often-overlooked aspect is handling connection states gracefully. I added a connection indicator and offline queue to ensure no data is lost during disconnections.

## Performance Considerations

With hundreds of documents updating per second, I implemented:
- **Debounced re-renders** to prevent UI jank
- **Virtual scrolling** for large data tables
- **Selective field listening** to minimize data transfer

The dashboard now handles 10,000+ concurrent connections with smooth 60fps animations.
